CMSC320 Final Project: Spotify Data Analysis for Germany and the U.S

Created by Michael Woods

Introduction

Spotify is a service I use all the time, and I've noticed that I often listen to German Music. That got me thinking; just how different is the music in germany and the U.S?

First, let's go over the importance of music in germany. Germany served as the source of many popular genres today, such as Classical Music, Electronic and more. They still serve as one of the major musical industries in the world, and are known for their experimental music.

The United States in another one of the largest musical industries in the world, with their influence spreading throughout the globe. Now, I tend to prefer german music, but this begs the question; is here really a difference in the music popular in Germany and the United States? I will examine this question from looking at the top 200 for each country from 2017 onwards using Spotipy. Spotipy is a library that allows me to extract music features; The features I will be looking at are danceability, energy, key, loudness, mode, speechines, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveliness, valence and tempo. I will also be comparing the popular genres of the two countries, and finally I will create a classifer to see if a given song would most likely be in the top 10 in Germany or the United States.

#getting the data
def getData(region_df):
    #initializing data frame with url
    element = region_df.head(1)["url"]
    firstTrack = sp.audio_features(element)
    #sp.audio_features returns an array of 1 element
    print(firstTrack[0].keys())
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns = firstTrack[0].keys())

    for index,element in region_df.iterrows():
        url = element["url"]
        rank = element["rank"]
        region = element["region"]
        chart = element["chart"]
        trend = element["trend"]
        streams = element["streams"]
        artist =  element["artist"]
        title =  element["title"]
        date =  element["date"]
        mytrack = sp.audio_features(url)[0]
        df2 = pd.DataFrame(mytrack, index=[0])

        #pd.concat([element, df2])
        #df.concat(e
        df2["rank"] = rank
        df2["artist"] = artist
        df2["title"] = title
        df2["date"] = date
        df2["chart"] = chart
        df2["trend"] = trend
        df2["streams"] = streams
        df2["region"] = region
        df = df.append(df2, ignore_index = True)
        
    return df

#since my dataset does not have the genre for the uri, I 
#took the liberty of collecting the data
def get_genre(df):
    
    for index,element in df.iterrows():
        #url = element["url"]
        artistName = element["artist"]
        result = sp.search(artistName)
        track = result['tracks']['items'][0]
        artist = sp.artist(track["artists"][0]["external_urls"]["spotify"])
    
        if (artist["genres"]):
            genre = artist["genres"][0]
            if (len(genre) >=3):
                if ("pop" in genre):
                    genre = "pop"
                elif ("rock" in genre):
                    genre = "rock"
                elif ("rap" in genre):
                    genre = "rap"  
                elif ("metal" in genre):
                    genre = "rap"  
                elif ("country" in genre):
                    genre = "rap"  
                elif ("rap" in genre):
                    genre = "rap"  
                elif ("electronic" in genre):
                    genre = "electronic"  
                elif ("hop" in genre):   
                    genre = "hip hop"
            df.iloc[index, df.columns.get_loc('genre')] = genre

#normalize the data for the scatter plot
def NormalizeData(data):
    return (data - np.min(data)) / (np.max(data) - np.min(data))

#plot the data
def plot(df, name, p1):
    #here I put a "rank2" so the higher values will be on the right for the scatter plot
    df["rank2"] = df["rank"] * -1 + 10
    #print(df [df["rank2"] < 2])
    standardized = NormalizeData(df["rank2"]).values
    standardized = df["rank2"].values
    Y = np.asarray(standardized).reshape(-1,1)
    if (p1 == "danceability"):
        X = np.array(df["danceability"].values).reshape(-1,1)
    elif (p1 == "energy"):
        X = np.array(df["energy"].values).reshape(-1,1)  
    elif (p1 == "loudness"):
        X = np.array(df["loudness"].values).reshape(-1,1)  
            
    elif (p1 == "instrumentalness"):
        X = np.array(df["loudness"].values).reshape(-1,1)  
    elif (p1 == "speechiness"):
        X = np.array(df["speechiness"].values).reshape(-1,1)      
    elif (p1 == "acousticness"):
        X = np.array(df["acousticness"].values).reshape(-1,1)  
    elif (p1 == "valence"):
        X = np.array(df["valence"].values).reshape(-1,1)  
    elif (p1 == "tempo"):
        X = np.array(df["tempo"].values).reshape(-1,1)  
    
    elif (p1 == "liveness"):
        X = np.array(df["liveness"].values).reshape(-1,1)      
    else:
        X = np.array(df["danceability"].values).reshape(-1,1)
    
    plt.scatter(Y,X)
    #plt.plot(X, model.predict(X), color = "red")
    plt.title(name)
    plt.show()

    corr_matrix = df.corr()

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
def plot_my_reg(df):
    lm = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    mat = np.matrix(america_df_final.drop(df.columns.difference(["acousticness", "energy"]), 1, inplace = False))
    X,Y = mat[:,0], mat[:,1]
    model = lm.fit(np.asarray(X),np.asarray(Y))
    m = model.coef_[0]
    b = model.intercept_
    print("linear Regression: y = {0}x + {1}".format(m, b))
    predicted_y = model.predict(df[["acousticness"]])
    R2 =   r2_score(df[['energy']], predicted_y)
    print(R2)
    axes = plt.gca()
    x_vals = np.array(axes.get_xlim())
    y_vals = b + m * x_vals
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))
    plt.scatter(np.asarray(df[ ["acousticness"]].values), np.asarray(df[ ["energy"]].values))
    plt.plot(x_vals, y_vals, '--')

Categorizing the Data:

For this approach, I decided to use a decision tree and random forest. A decision tree made the most sense hee for me because we have a set of attributes, and for that set of attributes, we map those attributes to a class. In this case our features will be the spotify features for the song and the respective rank for the song. Essentially, we want to find if a song will be in the top 10 us or top 10 germany.

Conclusion

Based on this data, it is possible to categorize whether a song would be in the top 10 in Germany or the US depending on the features and rank.

To summarize, we scraped our data, and found the relationship between a country and a given feature using violin plots. We then plotted said data on a violin plot with it's respective rank to see if there was any significant variability between each rank. After finally comparing all the components nad seein their respective differences, we moved on to categorizing the data into genres.

In categorizing the data into genres, we detirmined how popular each genre was popular in its respective country. We detirmined that the U.S like hip hop more, while the German seemingly had more rap. Overall, genre did not seem like the most important indicator because of the strong overlap between genres.

We also used a coorelation heatmap to detirmine how all the spotify features affect each other. What was the most interesting thing about the heatmap was the relationship between speechiness and danceability, where we found a positive coorealtion for the US, but a negative one for Germany.

We also plotted a Finally, we used a decision tree to classify if a song would belong in the top 10 of Germany or the US. With this, we got an accuracy of 62.8%; however, we could do better. Using a DecisionForest, we were able to find an even larger accuracy of 71.6%

Since we were able to find a classification algorithim that was quite accurate, I can deduce that there is merit to my preference of german music over music from the states.
